# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: document-chunking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] In computer programming, **chunking** has multiple meanings.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] Typical modern software systems allocate memory dynamically from structures known as heaps.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] Calls are made to heap-management routines to allocate and free memory.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] Heap management involves some computation time and can be a performance issue.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] **Chunking** refers to strategies for improving performance by using special knowledge of a situation to aggregate related memory-allocation requests.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] In data deduplication, data synchronization and remote data compression, Chunking is a process to split a file into smaller pieces called chunks by the chunking algorithm.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] It can help to eliminate duplicate copies of repeating data on storage, or reduces the amount of data sent over the network by only selecting changed chunks.
[src:document-chunking/chunking-computing] The Content-Defined Chunking (CDC) algorithm like Rolling hash and its variants have been the most popular data deduplication algorithms for the last 15 years.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Some authors regard semantic search as a set of techniques for retrieving knowledge from richly structured data sources like ontologies and XML as found on the Semantic Web.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Such technologies enable the formal articulation of domain knowledge at a high level of expressiveness and could enable the user to specify their intent in more detail at query time.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] The articulation enhances content relevance and depth by including specific places, people, or concepts relevant to the query.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Tools like Google's Knowledge Graph provide structured relationships between entities to enrich query interpretation.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Models like BERT and Sentence-BERT convert words or sentences into dense vectors for similarity comparison.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Semantic ontologies like Web Ontology Language, Resource Description Framework, and Schema.org organize concepts and relationships, allowing systems to infer related terms and deeper meanings.
[src:document-chunking/semantic-search] Hybrid search models combine lexical retrieval (e.g., BM25) with semantic ranking using pretrained transformer models for optimal performance.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] In natural language processing, a **sentence embedding** (or document embedding) is a representation of a natural language text as a vector of numbers which encodes meaningful semantic information.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] The name stems from the initially limitations of the approach to embed sequences of text longer than a sentence, but this is not longer a limitation.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] State of the art embeddings are based on the learned hidden layer representation of dedicated sentence transformer models.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] BERT pioneered an approach involving the use of a dedicated [CLS] token prepended to the beginning of each sentence inputted into the model; the final hidden state vector of this token encodes information about the sentence and can be fine-tuned for use in sentence classification tasks.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] In practice however, BERT's sentence embedding with the [CLS] token achieves poor performance, often worse than simply averaging non-contextual word embeddings.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] SBERT later achieved superior sentence embedding performance by fine tuning BERT's [CLS] token embeddings through the usage of a siamese neural network architecture on the SNLI dataset.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Other approaches are loosely based on the idea of distributional semantics applied to sentences.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Skip-Thought trains an encoder-decoder structure for the task of neighboring sentences predictions; this has been shown to achieve worse performance than approaches such as InferSent or SBERT.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] An alternative direction is to aggregate word embeddings, such as those returned by Word2vec, into sentence embeddings.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] The most straightforward approach is to simply compute the average of word vectors, known as continuous bag-of-words (CBOW).
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] However, more elaborate solutions based on word vector quantization have also been proposed.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] One such approach is the vector of locally aggregated word embeddings (VLAWE), which demonstrated performance improvements in downstream text classification tasks.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] In recent years, sentence embedding has seen a growing level of interest due to its applications in natural language queryable knowledge bases through the usage of vector indexing for semantic search.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] LangChain for instance utilizes sentence transformers for purposes of indexing documents.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] In particular, an indexing is generated by generating embeddings for chunks of documents and storing (document chunk, embedding) tuples.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Then given a query in natural language, the embedding for the query can be generated.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] A top k similarity search algorithm is then used between the query embedding and the document chunk embeddings to retrieve the most relevant document chunks as context information for question answering tasks.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] This approach is also known formally as retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Though not as predominant as BERTScore, sentence embeddings are commonly used for sentence similarity evaluation which sees common use for the task of optimizing a Large language model's generation parameters is often performed via comparing candidate sentences against reference sentences.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] By using the cosine-similarity of the sentence embeddings of candidate and reference sentences as the evaluation function, a grid-search algorithm can be utilized to automate hyperparameter optimization.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Multiple approaches exists for evaluating the quality of sentence embeddings typically covering one or multiple of the use-cases on models.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Some seek to measure whether the embedding is semantically meaningful by testing if semantically similar sentences appear closer together, while other sentence similarity or if embeddings reflect entailment using corpora such as Sentences Involving Compositional Knowledge (SICK), STS Bencmark.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Other approaches seek to measure the quality of the embeddings by how well it performs for downstream use-cases such as clustering, classification or semantic search.
[src:document-chunking/sentence-embedding] Comprehensive frameworks such as BEIR or MTEB that encapsulates multiple of these approaches have since become the standard to evaluate the quality of embedding across domains and/or languages.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Compare speech segmentation, the process of dividing speech into linguistically meaningful portions.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Word segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component words.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In English and many other languages using some form of the Latin alphabet, the space is a good approximation of a word divider (word delimiter), although this concept has limits because of the variability with which languages emically regard collocations and compounds.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In contrast, German compound nouns show less orthographic variation, with solidification being a stronger norm.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] However, the equivalent to the word space character is not found in all written scripts, and without it word segmentation is a difficult problem.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Languages which do not have a trivial word segmentation process include Chinese, Japanese, where sentences but not words are delimited, Thai and Lao, where phrases and sentences but not words are delimited, and Vietnamese, where syllables but not words are delimited.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In some writing systems however, such as the Ge'ez script used for Amharic and Tigrinya among other languages, words are explicitly delimited (at least historically) with a non-whitespace character.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] The Unicode Consortium has published a *Standard Annex on Text Segmentation*, exploring the issues of segmentation in multiscript texts.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Word splitting may also refer to the process of hyphenation.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Some scholars have suggested that modern Chinese should be written in word segmentation, with spaces between words like written English.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Because there are ambiguous texts where only the author knows the intended meaning.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] For example, "美国会不同意。" may mean "美国 会 不同意。" (The US will not agree.) or "美 国会 不同意。" (The US Congress does not agree).
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] For more details, see Chinese word-segmented writing.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Intent segmentation is the problem of dividing written words into keyphrases (2 or more group of words).
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In English and all other languages the core intent or desire is identified and become the corner-stone of the keyphrase Intent segmentation.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Core product/service, idea, action & or thought anchor the keyphrase.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Sentence segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component sentences.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In English and some other languages, using punctuation, particularly the full stop/period character is a reasonable approximation.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] However even in English this problem is not trivial due to the use of the full stop character for abbreviations, which may or may not also terminate a sentence.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] For example, *Mr.* is not its own sentence in "*Mr.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Smith went to the shops in Jones Street."* When processing plain text, tables of abbreviations that contain periods can help prevent incorrect assignment of sentence boundaries.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] As with word segmentation, not all written languages contain punctuation characters that are useful for approximating sentence boundaries.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Topic analysis consists of two main tasks: topic identification and text segmentation.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] While the first is a simple classification of a specific text, the latter case implies that a document may contain multiple topics, and the task of computerized text segmentation may be to discover these topics automatically and segment the text accordingly.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] The topic boundaries may be apparent from section titles and paragraphs.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] In other cases, one needs to use techniques similar to those used in document classification.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] It is also needed in topic detection and tracking systems and text summarizing problems.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Many different approaches have been tried: e.g.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] HMM, lexical chains, passage similarity using word co-occurrence, clustering, topic modeling, etc.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] It is quite an ambiguous task – people evaluating the text segmentation systems often differ in topic boundaries.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Hence, text segment evaluation is also a challenging problem.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Processes may be required to segment text into segments besides mentioned, including morphemes (a task usually called morphological analysis) or paragraphs.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Automatic segmentation is the problem in natural language processing of implementing a computer process to segment text.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] When punctuation and similar clues are not consistently available, the segmentation task often requires fairly non-trivial techniques, such as statistical decision-making, large dictionaries, as well as consideration of syntactic and semantic constraints.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Effective natural language processing systems and text segmentation tools usually operate on text in specific domains and sources.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] As an example, processing text used in medical records is a very different problem than processing news articles or real estate advertisements.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] The process of developing text segmentation tools starts with collecting a large corpus of text in an application domain.
[src:document-chunking/text-segmentation] Some text segmentation systems take advantage of any markup like HTML and know document formats like PDF to provide additional evidence for sentence and paragraph boundaries.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:document-chunking/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:document-chunking/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
